- How would you scale drift checks for high-throughput topics (>100K msg/sec)?
- What's your approach for schema evolution across multiple downstream consumers?

## Why This Is Asked
This question tests practical array manipulation skills while maintaining sorted order, a common frontend data processing task. It evaluates understanding of efficient algorithms and the ability to work with constraints (no mutation, sorted inputs).

## Key Concepts
- Two-pointer technique for merging sorted arrays
- Deduplication by comparing with the last added element
- Time and space complexity analysis
- Non-mutating operations

## Code Example
```javascript
function mergeUnique(a, b) {
  let i = 0, j = 0, result = [];

  while (i < a.length || j < b.length) {
    let current;

    if (j >= b.length || (i < a.length && a[i] <= b[j])) {
      current = a[i++];
    } else {
      current = b[j++];
    }

    if (result.length === 0 || result[result.length - 1] !== current) {
      result.push(current);
    }
  }

  return result;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you adapt this if inputs might not be sorted?
- What if we need to preserve the original order of first occurrence?
- How would this change for very large datasets that don't fit in memory?
- Could we optimize further if we know the range of possible tags?

